Title : Carl B. Olsen
Text : {{For|others of a similar name|Carl Olson (disambiguation){{!}}Carl Olson}}
'''Carl Baker Olsen''' (May 24, 1904 in [[Fort Collins, Colorado]] &ndash; March 4, 1998 in [[Escambia County, Florida]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Adm Carl Baker Olsen (1904-1998) |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/101090344/carl-baker-olsen |website=Find A Grave |accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Florida Death Index, 1877-1998 |url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VVZS-R4L |website=FamilySearch |accessdate=15 July 2018}}</ref>) was a [[Rear admiral (United States)|rear admiral]] in the [[United States Coast Guard]].

==Biography==
Olsen was born on May 24, 1904 in [[Fort Collins, Colorado]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uscg.mil/history/people/Flags/OlsenCBio.pdf|title=Rear Admiral Carl B. Olsen|publisher=United States Coast Guard|accessdate=2014-04-25}}</ref> He graduated from the [[California Institute of Technology]].

==Career==
Olsen graduated from the [[United States Coast Guard Academy]] in 1928. He was then stationed aboard the [[USCGC Mendota (WHEC-69)]], the [[USRC Seminole]] and the [[USS Ericsson (DD-56)]].

In 1932, Olsen completed aviation training at [[Naval Air Station Pensacola]]. From 1934 to 1936, he commanded [[Coast Guard Air Station Miami]]. In 1938, Olsen was awarded the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] for flying a critically ill [[United States Army]] [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]] approximately 300 miles during a storm, saving the officer's life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=33766|title=Carl B. Olsen|publisher=Military Times.com|accessdate=2014-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426235506/http://projects.militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=33766|archive-date=2014-04-26|dead-url=yes}}</ref> Later, he attended the [[Naval Postgraduate School]].

During [[World War II]], Olsen commanded the [[Coast Guard Air Station Clearwater|Coast Guard Air Station St. Petersburg]] before serving in the [[Asiatic-Pacific Theater|Pacific Theater of Operations]]. Awards he received for his service during the war include the [[Asiatic-Pacific Campaign Medal]], the [[American Defense Service Medal]], the [[American Campaign Medal]] and the [[World War II Victory Medal (United States)|World War II Victory Medal]].

After the war, he served as Chief of the Aviation Division of the Coast Guard from 1945 to 1946. From there, he served as Commandant of the Cadets at the Coast Guard Academy. Additionally, Olsen commanded the [[USCGC Eagle (WIX-327)]].

During the [[Korean War]], Olsen again served as Chief of the Aviation Division. For this, he received the [[National Defense Service Medal]].

Olsen retired from the Coast Guard in 1963.

